<LP>
   A principal law firm of American Continental Corp. and its
Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Association unit agreed to pay $20
million to settle suits filed by stockholders and bondholders
of the defunct thrift.
   In a statement released Friday, the New York law firm of
Kaye, Scholer, Fierman, Hays &amp; Handler said the settlement
represents less than two percent of the maximum total
recovery sought by the plaintiffs and is covered by the
firm's insurance policies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The law firm was an adviser to the thrift and Charles H.
Keating Jr., the former head of Lincoln and chairman of
American Continental.
   Almost 22,000 small investors purchased American
Continental bonds at the thrift's California branches. The
investors say they lost approximately $300 million when
American Continental collapsed and began operating under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code in April 1989. The
Lincoln Savings unit was seized by thrift regulators the same
month.
   The settlement covers all class action suits filed in
federal and California state courts. The allegations included
racketeering charges. The investors claimed they were
defrauded as a result of false financial statements made by
the thrift. The investors sought to recoup their losses from
Kaye Scholer and more than 60 other defendants, who they
allege bore some responsibility for the thrift's actions.
   "We are convinced that we committed no wrongdoing and are
not liable to anyone for the losses that have occurred," the
firm's statement said. The firm said it settled to avoid
protracted and costly litigation.
   Leonard Simon of Milberg Weiss Bershad Specthrie &amp; Lerach,
a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said the settlement represents a
"reasonable payment" by the law firm.
   One other defendant in the case has settled. In March, the
Los Angeles law firm of Parker, Milliken, Clark, O'Hara &amp;
Samuelian provisionally agreed to a settlement in which it
denied any wrongdoing. The arrangement calls for payment of
$4.3 million to the plaintiffs by the law firm's insurance
carriers and another $10 million in payments if that amount
isn't recouped from other defendants.
