   THE STATE OF MASSACHUSETTS hired a law firm on a
contingency fee basis.
   Usually the state pays its outside lawyers on an hourly
basis. However, in a contingency arrangement, five attorneys
from the Boston law firm of Dangel &amp; de Benedictis, will act
as special assistant attorneys general in an asbestos case.
They are representing the state in a suit to recover the
costs of repairing asbestos-contaminated, state-owned
buildings. The defendants are asbestos manufacturers and
distributors. The firm will be paid on a sliding scale of no
more than 30% of the potential recovery, which has been
estimated at more than $100 million, according to a spokesman
for the state attorney general's office.
   The contingency fee arrangement is expected to be cheaper
for the state than hourly payments because if it looses, it
will not pay fees, and will incur no more than $2.5 million
for expenses.
